<h3>Aldehydes & Ketones</h3>

@page "/aldehydes-ketones-notes"



<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Aldehydes and ketones are organic compounds containing a carbonyl group (<b>C=O</b>). They are part of the same functional group family but differ in the positioning of the carbonyl group.
</p>

<h2 style="color: deeppink; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Aldehydes:</b> General formula is <b>RCHO</b>, where <b>R</b> is an alkyl or hydrogen group, and the carbonyl group is always at the end of the carbon chain.</li>
    <li><b>Ketones:</b> General formula is <b>RCOR'</b>, where <b>R</b> and <b>R'</b> are alkyl or aryl groups, and the carbonyl group is within the carbon chain.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: deeppink; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Higher than alkanes but lower than alcohols due to the presence of dipole-dipole interactions rather than hydrogen bonding.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Lower aldehydes and ketones are soluble in water due to hydrogen bonding with water molecules. Solubility decreases as the carbon chain length increases.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: deeppink; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactions of Aldehydes and Ketones</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">Aldehydes and ketones undergo several characteristic reactions:</p>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Oxidation:</b>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Aldehydes:</b> Oxidized to carboxylic acids using oxidizing agents like acidified potassium dichromate (K<sub>2</sub>Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>).</li>
            <li><b>Ketones:</b> Generally resistant to oxidation unless under severe conditions.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li><b>Reduction:</b> Aldehydes and ketones can be reduced to primary and secondary alcohols, respectively, using reducing agents like sodium borohydride (NaBH<sub>4</sub>) or lithium aluminum hydride (LiAlH<sub>4</sub>).</li>
    <li>
        <b>Nucleophilic Addition:</b> Aldehydes and ketones react with nucleophiles like HCN to form hydroxynitriles. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>CHO + HCN → CH<sub>3</sub>CH(OH)CN</code>.
    </li>
    <li><b>Reaction with 2,4-DNP:</b> Both aldehydes and ketones form orange/yellow precipitates with 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine, which can help identify the compound.</li>
</ol>

